	abstract = {Community radio is a powerful, undisputed and widely used communication mass medium for information sharing to rural audiences across Africa due to its low cost, accessibility, popularity, participatory approach and ability to penetrate marginalised farmers of developing countries. As access to proven agricultural information is crucial to farmers, this study examined how Community Radio Broadcast (CRB) could be used to complement agricultural extension service delivery in South Africa targeting smallholder farmers. A total of 167 community radio stations (CRS) with usable data were analysed from South Africa. Based on programming format, language of communication used, listenership and target audience by CRS, a questionnaire was prepared for station managers. All public domain CRS websites were accessed to analyse the programming. The results indicated that amongst the sampled CRS, local languages are popular for programme presentations with English being used by more than 50\% of the CRS. The target audience was varied and diversified; however, only 2.85\% out of nine provinces are targeting farmers. Listenership distribution is large, cutting across different age groups with an average listenership of 964 000/province/day. However, the number of agricultural programmes aired on South African CRS is very limited. In an attempt to use CRB as an avenue for reaching the smallholder farmers, the study suggests an Agricultural Radio Information System (ARIS) model as a strategy to complement agricultural extension advisory services of South Africa.},
