	doi = {10.1086/452188},
	abstract = {In this article, the effectiveness of a multimedia extension program targeted at Honduran farmers who have low human capital investments and whose traditional farming methods are being threatened by radical changes in their resource bases are analysed. Dichotomous, yes or no decisions were examined in a binary logistic regression. Farmers were asked to identify their sources of learning. Institutional and human capital variables were included to diminish other forms of bias and to identify which groups of farmers are amenable to adopting new technologies. An extension program for a region in Honduras was analysed to determine what types of farmers are responsive to new technologies and what types of training promote the adoption of those technologies. Producers of commercial crops demonstrated an increasing inclination to adopt new technologies as they increased the market proportion of their output. Subsistence farmers demonstrated a negative correlation between land extensiveness and technology adoption. Cooperative association had a positive influence on adoption. The results indicate that training and visitation extension methods have a multiplier effect through personal contacts of experts and friends and are very effective in motivating technology adoption. Mass communication media cannot be discounted and present a viable alternative. -from Authors},
